description.value: Scaraboid made of faience, with a roughly rectangular ground shape, the back is curved, the base flat. Few traces of the glazing is preserved inside the signs of the base, whitish colour.  The back shows traces of an original carving of some sort of an animal(?) or decorative pattern, but the stage is preservation is so bad that no identification is possible anymore.  The seal at the base shows three very crude cut signs, on the left a seated deity facing to the right, on top of a possible nb-sign, in front of both an unspecific oval sign.  Perforated along its longitudinal side.

description.value: Oval, transparent rock crystal scaraboid with a domed back. Incised design including single-line border and field dividers. Intermediate between a three-register and a nine-compartment layout; the tops and bottoms of the vertical field dividers consist of 'ankh' signs. Four-winged beetle in central compartment, uraei with coiled tails on both sides; seated anthropomorphic, falcon-headed Horus figures in top and bottom compartments, each holding a malformed 'ankh' or 'maat' sign; empty "corner" compartments; letters of inscription, three of them inverted, added in empty spaces. Chipped.

description.value: Terracotta scaraboid-mould, with impression in form of African head, with distinctive features. Hair undecorated, hairline marked by three curved lines, forehead grooved with horizontal, parallel lines, separated by a V-shaped groove which springs from the top of the nose. Protruding eyes, nose and mouth. Small ears indicated on smooth band above face, perhaps added by hand. Details of impression are modelled right up to edge of mould. No exact parallels amongst scaraboids in BM collection.
